{
  "sectionCode": "514",
  "sectionCodeDisplay": "514",
  "title": "Language and Communication",
  "outline": [
    {
      "level": "A",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Communication as a foundation of human culture and as the essential element in social and cultural interaction, the role of communication in the modification of human behaviour",
      "children": []
    },
    {
      "level": "B",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Nonverbal communication",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Communication by means of bodily gestures and posture, by facial expression",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Laughter and nonword sounds as communication",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The use of signals, signs, symbols, icons, and cultural artifacts",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "4",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Cybernetic communication: computer languages, human language-computer interfaces, and artificial intelligence and expert systems",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "5",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Parapsychological forms of communication: telepathy [see 432. H.]",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "C",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "The nature of language",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Definitions of language",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Ways of studying language: phonetics, grammar, semantics",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Language variants: dialects, slang, and specialized variants (e.g jargon, pidgins, creoles)",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "4",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Speech: the psychological and physiological bases",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "5",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Meaning and style in language: structural and lexical meanings; semantic flexibility; language and conceptualization; style",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "6",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Language and culture: transmission of language; language and social differentiation; control of language for cultural ends; language learning and literacy; written language and spoken language",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "7",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Linguistic change and language typology",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "8",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Cryptology: codes, ciphers, and other means of encrypting language",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "D",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "The structure of speech and language",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The phonetics of speech (articulatory, acoustic, linguistic); phonetic transcription; experimental phonetics",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The physiology of speech: regulators (respiratory and brain functions); the larynx; voice production (including synthetic voice production)",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Speech disorders",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "E",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Written language: systems of notation",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The nature, origin, and evolution of writing: from pictures to the alphabet",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Types of writing systems: logographic, syllabic, consonantal, alphabetic, featural",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Systems of writing: hieroglyphic, cuneiform, alphabetic, ideographic",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "4",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Adjuncts to writing: punctuation, shorthand",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "5",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Calligraphy and the art of handwriting: early Semitic, Arabic, Greek, Latin, Indie, East Asian",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "F",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Linguistics: the scientific study of language and language development [see also 10/36 H.]",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The development of linguistic theory",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Synchronic linguistics: structural, transformational-generative grammar, tagmemics, stratificational grammar, the Prague school",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Diachronic linguistics: linguistic change, comparative method, language classification",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "4",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Dialectology and the study of linguistic geography",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "5",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Semantics: the study of language and meaning",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "6",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The study of writing",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "7",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The classification of language",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "G",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Language and society",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Attitudes toward language: taboos in language use, myths about the origin of language, the relation of language and thought",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The connection of language with history, the role of language in the transmission of culture",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The role of language in cross-cultural relations",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "4",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The use of language as a political instrument",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "5",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The role of language in unifying social and occupational groups",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    },
